wiki_catalogs.name: System Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the System Overview section focused on the CodingIT-1 platform. Explain its purpose as an AI-powered full-stack development environment that transforms natural language into working applications. Describe the architecture spanning web and desktop clients, secure code execution via E2B sandboxes, and multi-framework support. Document the relationship between components including Next.js frontend, Supabase backend, Electron desktop wrapper, and AI integration. Include high-level diagrams illustrating system context and data flow. Provide beginner-friendly explanations of core concepts like natural language to code generation, real-time preview, and deployment workflows. Highlight key differentiators such as 50+ AI model support and secure isolated execution. Use terminology consistent with the codebase like 'morph-chat', 'sandbox', and 'tasks'.

wiki_catalogs.name: API Endpoints
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create API documentation for the core API endpoint groups in the CodingIT-1 backend. Document the RESTful design patterns used in Next.js API routes, including route handlers for chat interactions, file operations, GitHub integration, sandbox management, task tracking, and terminal commands. For each endpoint group, specify HTTP methods, URL structures, request/response schemas, and authentication requirements. Explain the use of Server Actions and route handlers in the App Router context. Include examples of request payloads and error responses. Detail middleware.ts protections applied to these endpoints and describe rate-limiting or security measures. Address integration with external services like GitHub and E2B sandboxes, and provide client usage patterns from both web and desktop applications.

wiki_catalogs.name: Component Tree
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the Component Tree architecture in CodingIT-1. Explain the hierarchical structure starting from the root layout.tsx and page.tsx, detailing how layout wrappers and providers are composed. Document the role of shared UI components in components/ui based on shadcn/ui and Radix UI primitives, and their extension in apps/desktop/app/components for desktop-specific needs. Illustrate how atomic components are composed into complex UIs such as chat interfaces, file trees, and settings panels. Include examples of component composition patterns from chat.tsx, sidebar.tsx, and workbench components. Address cross-platform consistency between web and desktop clients, responsive design implementation using Tailwind CSS, and accessibility practices. Provide guidance on creating new components following existing patterns and integrating them into the component hierarchy.

wiki_catalogs.name: Chat API
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive API documentation for the Chat API endpoints in CodingIT-1. Document the POST /api/chat endpoint for initiating AI conversations, including request structure with message history, model selection, and system prompts. Detail the streaming response mechanism using ReadableStream and SSE for real-time chat output. Explain the morph-chat endpoint for advanced conversation transformations and the codeInterpreter functionality for executing code within chat context. Provide examples of request payloads for different AI models and response parsing strategies. Document integration with the frontend Chat component and error recovery mechanisms for interrupted streams.

wiki_catalogs.name: Database Models

wiki_overview.content:
<blog>
# Comprehensive Project Analysis: CodingIT

## 1. Project Introduction

### Purpose Statement
CodingIT is an open-source AI-powered full-stack development platform that transforms natural language into working applications. It serves as an AI co-developer capable of building, testing, and deploying full-stack applications across multiple frameworks.

### Core Goals and Objectives
- Enable developers to create production-ready applications using natural language prompts
- Support 50+ AI models from various providers for comprehensive code generation capabilities
- Provide secure code execution through isolated E2B containers
- Offer both web and desktop applications for flexible development environments
- Support multiple frameworks including Next.js, Vue, Streamlit, and Gradio

### Target Audience
- Developers seeking AI-assisted coding capabilities
- Teams looking for collaborative AI development platforms
- Individuals wanting to build applications without deep programming knowledge
- Enterprises requiring secure, production-ready AI development environments

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown
The project follows a monorepo architecture with two main applications:
- **Web Application** (`@codinit/web`): Next.js 14 application deployed on Vercel
- **Desktop Application** (`@codinit/desktop`): Electron-based native application

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[CodingIT Monorepo] --> B[Web Application]
    A --> C[Desktop Application]
    B --> D[Next.js 14]
    B --> E[Supabase PostgreSQL]
    C --> F[Remix + Electron]
    C --> G[Cloudflare D1 SQLite]
    D --> H[Vercel Deployment]
    F --> I[Desktop Installers]
```

### Design Patterns
The architecture implements several key design patterns:

- **Monorepo Structure**: Using pnpm workspaces to manage multiple packages
- **Server Actions**: Next.js App Router with server-side functionality
- **Component Library**: Reusable UI components based on shadcn/ui and Radix UI
- **State Management**: Nanostores for lightweight state management
- **API Routes**: File-based routing for API endpoints

### System Relationships
The system components interact through well-defined interfaces:

```mermaid
graph TD
    Client[Client Browser] --> WebApp[Web Application]
    Desktop[Desktop App] --> Electron[Electron Runtime]
    WebApp --> Supabase[Supabase Database]
    Desktop --> Cloudflare[Cloudflare D1]
    WebApp --> E2B[E2B Sandboxes]
    Desktop --> WebContainer[WebContainer API]
    WebApp --> AIProviders[AI Providers]
    Desktop --> AIProviders
    AIProviders --> OpenAI[OpenAI]
    AIProviders --> Anthropic[Anthropic]
    AIProviders --> Google[Gemini]
    AIProviders --> Mistral[Mistral]
    AIProviders --> Ollama[Ollama]
```

### Data Flow
The data flow follows a structured pattern from user input to execution:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[User Input] --> B[Natural Language Processing]
    B --> C[Code Generation]
    C --> D[Code Execution Environment]
    D --> E[E2B Sandbox/WebContainer]
    E --> F[Real-time Preview]
    F --> G[User Interface]
    G --> H[Feedback Loop]
    H --> A
    C --> I[Database Operations]
    I --> J[Supabase/Cloudflare D1]
    J --> C
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- **Web Application**: `app/page.tsx` - Main application page
- **Desktop Application**: `apps/desktop/app/root.tsx` - Desktop app entry point
- **API Routes**: `app/api/` directory for server-side endpoints
- **Layout Components**: `app/layout.tsx` for shared layout structure

Sources:
- [page.tsx](app/page.tsx)
- [root.tsx](apps/desktop/app/root.tsx)
- [layout.tsx](app/layout.tsx)

### Core Modules
- **AI Integration**: `lib/models.ts` and `lib/models.json` for AI provider configuration
- **Authentication**: `lib/auth.ts` and Supabase integration for user management
- **Sandbox Management**: `lib/sandbox.ts` for E2B container operations
- **State Management**: `lib/stores` for application state
- **UI Components**: `components/ui` for reusable component library

Sources:
- [models.ts](lib/models.ts)
- [models.json](lib/models.json)
- [auth.ts](lib/auth.ts)
- [sandbox.ts](lib/sandbox.ts)

### Configuration Approach
The project uses a comprehensive configuration system:

- **Environment Variables**: Managed through `.env.local` file
- **Build Configuration**: `next.config.mjs` for Next.js settings
- **TypeScript Configuration**: `tsconfig.json` for compiler options
- **Package Management**: `pnpm-workspace.yaml` for monorepo setup
- **Styling**: `tailwind.config.ts` for Tailwind CSS configuration

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Environment Variables] --> B[Application]
    C[Configuration Files] --> B
    D[Package Dependencies] --> B
    B --> E[Build Process]
    E --> F[Development Server]
    E --> G[Production Build]
```

Sources:
- [next.config.mjs](next.config.mjs)
- [tsconfig.json](tsconfig.json)
- [tailwind.config.ts](tailwind.config.ts)
- [pnpm-workspace.yaml](pnpm-workspace.yaml)

### External Dependencies
The project leverages numerous external dependencies for enhanced functionality:

- **AI SDKs**: @ai-sdk/openai, @ai-sdk/anthropic, @ai-sdk/google
- **UI Libraries**: @radix-ui/react components, lucide-react icons
- **Database**: @supabase/supabase-js for PostgreSQL access
- **Analytics**: posthog-js for product analytics
- **Code Editing**: @monaco-editor/react for code editor
- **Styling**: tailwindcss for utility-first CSS

Sources:
- [package.json](package.json)
- [apps/desktop/package.json](apps/desktop/package.json)

### Integration Points
Key integration points include:

- **AI Providers**: OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, Mistral, Ollama
- **Authentication**: Supabase Auth with Row Level Security
- **Payments**: Stripe for subscription billing
- **Deployment**: Vercel for web app, Electron builders for desktop
- **Code Execution**: E2B SDK for secure sandboxing
- **Analytics**: PostHog for usage tracking

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[CodingIT Platform] --> B[AI Providers]
    A --> C[Supabase Auth]
    A --> D[Stripe Billing]
    A --> E[Vercel Deployment]
    A --> F[E2B Sandboxes]
    A --> G[PostHog Analytics]
    B --> H[OpenAI]
    B --> I[Anthropic]
    B --> J[Google]
    B --> K[Mistral]
    B --> L[Ollama]
```

Sources:
- [lib/api-keys.ts](lib/api-keys.ts)
- [lib/supabase-server.ts](lib/supabase-server.ts)
- [lib/telemetry-service.ts](lib/telemetry-service.ts)

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview
CodingIT offers a comprehensive set of features for AI-powered development:

- **Natural Language to Code**: Transform text prompts into working applications
- **Multi-Framework Support**: Development environments for Next.js, Vue, Streamlit, Gradio
- **Real-time Collaboration**: Shared workspaces and team management
- **Secure Execution**: Isolated sandboxes for safe code execution
- **Version Control**: Git integration for code management
- **Deployment Options**: Web and desktop application availability

### Implementation Highlights
- **AI Model Management**: Dynamic loading of 50+ AI models from various providers
- **Sandbox Templates**: Pre-configured environments for different development scenarios
- **Component Library**: Extensive UI components built with shadcn/ui patterns
- **State Management**: Efficient state handling with Nanostores
- **API Design**: RESTful API routes for various functionalities

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Idle
    Idle --> CodeGeneration: User Prompt
    CodeGeneration --> CodeExecution: Generate Code
    CodeExecution --> Preview: Execute in Sandbox
    Preview --> Idle: Display Results
    CodeGeneration --> Error: Invalid Input
    CodeExecution --> Error: Execution Failed
    Error --> Idle: Show Error Message
```

Sources:
- [lib/models.ts](lib/models.ts)
- [sandbox-templates](sandbox-templates)
- [components/ui](components/ui)
- [app/api](app/api)
</blog>
